Analytical Lasso solution with Helmert design matrix¶

Key observation is that the design matrix (first $p$ columns of a Helmert matrix) has orthonormal columns. Therefore \begin{eqnarray*} & & \frac 12 |y - X \beta|2^2 + \lambda \sum{j=2}^p |\beta_j| \ &=& \frac 12 (\beta^T X^T X \beta - 2 y^T X \beta + y^T y) + \lambda \sum_{j=2}^p |\beta_j| \ &=& \frac 12 (\beta^T \beta - 2 y^T X \beta + y^T y) + \lambda \sum_{j=2}^p |\beta_j| \ &=& \frac 12 \sum{j=1}^p (\beta_j - y^T x{\cdot j})^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=2}^p |\beta_j| + c. \end{eqnarray*} It is immediate that the minimizer is given by $\hat \beta_1(\lambda) = y^T x_{\cdot 1}$ and $\hat \beta_j(\lambda) = ST(x_{\cdot j}^T y, \lambda)$ for $j=2,\ldots,p$.

Now let's generate design matrix and responses.

In [3]:
include("hw7.jl")
# design matrix is transpose of the Helmert matrix
srand(2015790003)
n = 10000
p = 1000
H = helmert(n)'
X = H[:, 1:p]
println(countnz(X) / length(X)) # sparsity
β = zeros(size(X, 2))
k = 5 # number of non-zeros
β[1:k] = 1:k
y = X * β + randn(n)
penidx = [false, trues(size(X, 2) - 1)]

# set up grid and compute the analytical solution
λlist = convert(Vector{Float64}, 0.0:0.6:6.0)
βhattrue = zeros(size(X, 2), length(λlist))
xty = X' * y
for i = 1:length(λlist)
    βhattrue[:, i] = copysign(max(abs(xty) - λlist[i], 0.0), xty)
    βhattrue[1, i] = xty[1]
end

#
# This function fits lasso regression with responses y and design matrix X.
# The logical vector penidx indiciates which predictors are penalized.
#
function lsqlassopath(y::Vector{Float64}, X::Matrix{Float64},
                      λgrid::Vector{Float64}=[0.0];
                      algo::String="Convex.jl", maxiter::Int=1000,
                      objtol::Float64=1e-4, penidx::BitArray{1}=trues(size(X, 2)))

  # allocate space for solution
  p = size(X, 2)
  ngrid = length(λgrid)
  βhat = zeros(p, ngrid)

  # pre-compute sum-of-squares of columns of X
  xjnrm2 = squeeze(sumabs2(X, 1), 1)

  # path following from large λ
  if all(penidx)
    for i = ngrid:-1:1
      λ = λgrid[i]
      if i == ngrid
        # cold start
        βhat[:, i] = lsqlasso(y, X, λ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                              objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2)
      else
        # warm start
        βhat[:, i] = lsqlasso(y, X, λ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                              objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2, β0=βhat[:, i+1])
      end
    end
  else
    X1 = X[:, !penidx] # unpenalized predictors
    X2 = X[:, penidx]  # penalized predictors
    X1U, X1σ, X1V = svd(X1, thin=true)
    ywork = y - X1U * (X1U' * y)
    Xwork = X2 - X1U * (X1U' * X2)
    for i = ngrid:-1:1
      λ = λgrid[i]
      if i == ngrid
        # cold start
        βhat[penidx, i] = lsqlasso(ywork, Xwork, λ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                                   objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2[penidx])
      else
        # warm start
        #βhat[penidx, i] = lsqlasso(ywork, Xwork, λ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
        #                           objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2[penidx],
        #                           β0=βhat[penidx, i+1])
        βhat[penidx, i] = lsqlasso(ywork, Xwork, λ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                                   objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2[penidx])
      end
      βhat[!penidx, i] = X1V * ((X1U' * (y - X2 * βhat[penidx, i])) ./ X1σ)
    end
  end

  return βhat
end

#
# This function fits lasso regression with responses y and design matrix X.
# This function assumes all predictors are penalized. If X = (X1, X2), where
# X1 is not penalized, we can project y and X2 to the null space of X', then
# call this function.
#
function lsqlasso(y::Vector{Float64}, X::Matrix{Float64}, λ::Float64=0.0;
                  algo::String="Convex.jl",
                  β0::Vector{Float64}=zeros(size(X, 2)),
                  maxiter::Int=1000, objtol::Float64=1e-4,
                  xjnrm2::Vector{Float64}=sumabs2(X, 1))

  # Retrieve dimensions
  n, p = size(X)

  if algo == "Convex.jl"

    # Create optimization variables
    βhat = Convex.Variable(size(X, 2))
    # Set up optmization problem
    problem = Convex.minimize(0.5 * Convex.sum_squares(y - X * βhat)
                              + λ * Convex.norm(βhat, 1))
    # Solve the problem
    Convex.solve!(problem)
    # Return
    βhat.value

  elseif algo == "CD"

    # initial point
    βhat = copy(β0)
    # resid = y - X * βhat
    resid = copy(y)
    BLAS.gemv!('N', -1.0, X, βhat, 1.0, resid)
    objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) + λ * sumabs(βhat)
    ptrres = pointer(resid)
    ptrinc = n * sizeof(Float64) # increment for pointer
    for iter = 1:maxiter
      # Renew the pointer
      ptrxj = pointer(X)
      # Update βj
      for j = 1:p
        # these two lines are ~10 times slower; pointer helps a lot!
        # tmp = βhat[j] + dot(X[:, j], resid) / xjnrm2[j]
        # tmp = βhat[j] + BLAS.dot(n, X[:, j], 1, resid, 1) / xjnrm2[j]
        tmp = βhat[j] + BLAS.dot(n, ptrxj, 1, ptrres, 1) / xjnrm2[j]
        if abs(tmp) > λ / xjnrm2[j]
          tmp = copysign(abs(tmp) - λ / xjnrm2[j], tmp) # soft-thresholding
          BLAS.axpy!(n, βhat[j] - tmp, ptrxj, 1, ptrres, 1) # update residual
          βhat[j] = tmp
        end
        ptrxj += ptrinc # advance pointer
      end
      # Check convergence criterion
      objvalold = objval
      objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) + λ * sumabs(βhat)
      if abs(objvalold - objval) < objtol * (abs(objvalold) + 1.0)
        break
      end
    end
    # return
    βhat

  elseif algo == "ISTA"

    # initial point
    βhat = copy(β0)
    resid = y - X * βhat # use axpy?
    objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) + λ * sumabs(βhat)
    # initial step length and line search max iteration
    s::Float64 = 1.0
    #s = eigs(X' * X; nev=1, maxiter=5, ritzvec=false, which=:LM)[1][1]
    lsmaxiter::Int = 10
    # allocate intermediate variable
    βnew = zeros(βhat)
    grad = zeros(βhat)
    for iter = 1:maxiter
      # Update gradient
      # grad = - X' * resid
      BLAS.gemv!('T', -1.0, X, resid, 0.0, grad)
      # Line search loop
      for lsiter = 1:lsmaxiter
        βnew = βhat - s * grad # use BLAS
        # Soft-thresholding
        @simd for j = 1:p
          @inbounds βnew[j] = copysign(max(abs(βnew[j]) - s * λ, 0.0), βnew[j])
        end
        residnew = y - X * βnew # use BLAS
        objnew = 0.5 * sumabs2(residnew) #+ λ * sumabs(βnew)
        # TODO: change this to looping
        surnew = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) + dot(βnew - βhat, grad) +
          0.5 / s * sumabs2(βnew - βhat) #+ λ * sumabs(βnew)
        if objnew <= surnew
          βhat = copy(βnew)
          resid = copy(residnew)
          break
        else
          s /= 2.0
        end
      end
      # Check convergence criterion
      objvalold = objval
      objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) + λ * sumabs(βhat)
      if abs(objvalold - objval) < objtol * (abs(objvalold) + 1.0)
        break
      end
    end
    # return
    βhat

  end

end

#
# This function generates the Helmert matrix of size n.
#
function helmert(n::Int)

  H = zeros(n, n)
  H[:, 1] = 1 / sqrt(n)
  for j = 2:n
    H[1:j-1, j] = 1 / sqrt(j * (j - 1))
    H[j, j] = - (j - 1) / sqrt(j * (j - 1))
  end
  H = H'

end
